t m3 xb8 hd0 y1221 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws5">in<span class="_ _2"></span>v<span class="_ _2"></span>olves second deri<span class="_ _2"></span>vati<span class="_ _3"></span>ves. Let’<span class="_ _3"></span>s see what we can guess about the form of the solution </div><div class="t m3 xb8 hd0 y520f ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">directly from the equation. <span class="_ _2"></span>W<span class="_ _17"></span>e can rewrite Equation 3 in the form</div><div class="c x1a0 ye699 wf43 h22b"><div class="t m3 x70 h137 y955 ff23f fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">d</div><div class="t m3 xf h13c y11f2 ff23e fs4f fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">2</div><div class="t m3 x84 h137 y955 ff23f fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">x</div><div class="t m3 x1b h137 y21 ff23f fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">d<span class="_ _4"></span>t</div></div><div class="t m3 x1f5 h13c y35d8 ff23e fs4f fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">2</div><div class="t m3 x24d h150 ya7d ff240 fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">−<span class="_ _1b"> </span><span class="ff242">2</span></div><div class="c x1a0 ye699 wf43 h22b"><div class="t m3 xa2 h137 y955 ff23f fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">k</div><div class="t m3 xb5 h137 y21 ff23f fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">m</div></div><div class="t m3 x47 hd0 ya7d ff23e fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="c x1a0 ye699 wf43 h22b"><div class="t m3 x77 h137 y952 ff23f fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">x</div></div><div class="t m3 xb8 hd0 y1225 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws54">This says that the second deri<span class="_ _2"></span>vati<span class="_ _2"></span>ve of </div><div class="c x1e7 y2c35 w175 h167"><div class="t m3 x0 h137 y21 ff23f fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">x</div></div><div class="t m3 x1ca hd0 y1225 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws54"> is proportional to </div><div class="c x37 y2c35 w175 h167"><div class="t m3 x0 h137 y21 ff23f fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">x</div></div><div class="t m3 x2a7 hd0 y1225 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws54"> but has the opposite sign. <span class="_ _3"></span>W<span class="_ _3"></span>e </div><div class="t m3 xb8 hd0 yb93 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws5d">kno<span class="_ _2"></span>w two functions with this property<span class="_ _3"></span>, the sine and cosine functions. In fact, it turns out </div><div class="t m3 xb8 hd0 y2733 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws5b">that all solutions of Equation 3 can be written as combinations of certain sine and cosine </div><div class="t m3 xb8 hd0 y105c ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws2c">functions (see Exercise 16). <span class="_ _2"></span>This is not surprising; we expect the spring to oscillate about </div><div class="t m3 xb8 hd0 y105d ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws66">its equilibrium position and so it is natural to think that trigonometric functions are </div><div class="t m3 xb8 hd0 y95b ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">in<span class="_ _2"></span>v<span class="_ _2"></span>olved.</div><div class="t m3 xb8 h157 yef46 ff23d fs54 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0">■ </div><div class="t m3 x2cd hd3 ya95 ff237 fs3e fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">General Dieren<span class="_ _2"></span>tial Equations</div><div class="t m3 xb8 hd7 y63d ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 lsb2 wsd4">In general, a <span class="ff239">differential equation</span> is an equation that contains an unkno<span class="_ _3"></span>wn function and<span class="_ _4"></span> </div><div class="t m3 xb8 hd7 y63e ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 lsb2 ws25">one or more of its deriv<span class="_ _3"></span>atives. <span class="_ _3"></span>The <span class="ff239 wsdd">order</span> of a differential equation is the order of the high<span class="ls0 ws0">-</span></div><div class="t m3 xb8 hd0 y63f ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 lsb2 ws6a">est deri<span class="_ _2"></span>vati<span class="_ _2"></span>ve that occurs in the equation. <span class="_ _2"></span>Thus Equations 1 and 2 are rst-order equations </div><div class="t m3 xb8 hd0 y640 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 lsb2 ws6a">and Equation 3 is a second-order equation. In all three of those equations the independent </div><div class="t m3 xb8 hd0 y641 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 lsb2 ws45">v<span class="_ _2"></span>ariable is called </div><div class="c x1fc yef47 w16c h15c"><div class="t m3 x0 h137 y21 ff23f fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">t</div></div><div class="t m3 x24e hd0 y641 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 lsb2 ws45"> and represents time, but in general the independent v<span class="_ _3"></span>ariable doesn’t </div><div class="t m3 xb8 hd0 y642 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 lsb2 ws0">hav<span class="_ _2"></span>e to represent time. For e<span class="_ _2"></span>xample, when we consider the differential equation</div><div class="t m3 x71 hf8 yef48 ff19 fs3 fc5 sc0 ls0 ws0">4</div><div class="t m3 x27b h66 y921f ff23a fs7 fc6 sc0 ls0 ws0"> </div><div class="c x1c5 y2f1e w2b1a h406"><div class="t m3 x0 h137 ya0 ff23f fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">y<span class="ff242">9<span class="_ _1b"> </span><span class="ff240">−<span class="_ _11"> </span></span></span>x<span class="_ _4"></span>y</div></div><div class="t m3 xb8 hd0 y8ca6 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">it is understood that </div><div class="c x197 y9bfc w175 h18a"><div class="t m3 x0 h137 ya0 ff23f fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">y</div></div><div class="t m3 x149 hd0 y8ca6 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0"> is an unknown function of </div><div class="c x23 yef49 w17d h167"><div class="t m3 x0 h137 y21 ff23f fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">x</div></div><div class="t m3 x177 hd0 y8ca6 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">.</div><div class="t m3 x82 hd0 y3237 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws61">A function </div><div class="c x10c yef4a w173 h9d"><div class="t m3 x70 h137 ya0 ff23f fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">f</div></div><div class="t m3 x7e hd7 y3237 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws61"> is called a <span class="ff239 ws0">solution</span> of a differential equation if the equation is satised </div><div class="t m3 xb8 hd0 y4908 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">when </div><div class="c x8a y4907 w15d h14e"><div class="t m3 x0 hde ya0 ff23f fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws0">y<span class="_ _1b"> </span><span class="ff240">−<span class="_ _11"> </span></span>f<span class="_ _9"></span><span class="ff241">s<span class="_ _4"></span></span>x<span class="ff241">d</span></div></div><div class="t m3 x109 hd0 y4908 ff23a fs3 fc1 sc0 ls0 ws